    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-02-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-02-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="459"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d459">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 656.119/231½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of The <gloss type="from">Assistant</gloss> to the
                        Counselor for the Department of State</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_AG1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Auchincloss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-02-25">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 25, 1918</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Dutch Minister called and spoke very earnestly about the present situation in
                    Holland with respect to grains. He handed me a copy of a cable received from the
                    Minister for Foreign Affairs, which I attach hereto.<note n="1" xml:id="d459fn1"
                        >Not printed.</note> He stated that two things were troubling him:</p>
                <list>
                    <label>(1)</label>
                    <item>The fact that the negotiations carried on in London apparently were not
                        final and had to be referred to the War Trade Board for approval;</item>
                    <label>(2)</label>
                    <item>That the United States did not recognize the fact that the Dutch
                        Government could not carry through any agreement which was not approved by
                        Germany.</item>
                </list>
                <p>He begged most earnestly for releases of grain so as to forestall riots and
                    disturbances which he said would occur in Holland were the food shortage to
                    continue.</p>
                <p>He said that he wanted very much to have the <hi rend="italic">Nieuw
                        Amsterdam</hi> return to Holland at the earliest possible moment<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d459fn2">It had arrived on Feb. 7.</note> so as to prove to his
                    Government that the American Government would live up to its promise to permit
                    this boat to return, provided the assurance was given this Government that the
                        <hi rend="italic">Nieuw Amsterdam</hi> would return here forthwith.</p>
                <p>He said that it would be very satisfactory if the cargo of the <hi rend="italic"
                        >Samarinda</hi>, now at Norfolk, which amounted to 7,000 tons of rice could
                    be loaded on the <hi rend="italic">Nieuw Amsterdam</hi> on her return trip,
                    together with certain oil cakes referred to in the telegram. I promised to do
                    what I could for him with Mr. <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_MVC1"
                        >McCormick</persName>. He said that he felt that he must ask for an audience
                    with the President so as to acquaint him with the desperate situation now
                    prevalent in Holland. He said that if we were not a little bit more generous
                    they would be forced to accede to Germany’s terms.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_AG1">A[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                                >uchincloss</hi>]</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
